The Rule of 72 is a way to estimate how long it takes for a given value to double. In this rule, we basically divide $72$ by the rate. This will essentially give us an estimate number of periods before the given amount is doubled.

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Time}&=\dfrac{72}{\text{Rate}}
\end{aligned}$$

However, the Rule of 73 is a much more accurate rule to follow if the rate is given at $10\%$. To show this, we will use the formula for the future value:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Future value}&=\text{Present value} \times (1+\text{Rate})^\text{time}
\end{aligned}$$

For this, we will assume a present value of $\$1$ and time as $7.3$.
